The nature and frequency of medical emergencies among patients in a dental 
school setting.

Anders PL(1), Comeau RL, Hatton M, Neiders ME.

Author information:
(1)Department of Oral Diagnostic Sciences, University at Buffalo School of 
Dental Medicine, Buffalo, NY 14214, USA. planders@buffalo.edu

As health care improves and life expectancy increases, dentists and dental 
students are treating a growing number of elderly and medically compromised 
patients, increasing the likelihood of a medical emergency during treatment. 
Previous studies examining emergencies in a dental setting have relied upon 
self-reports and are therefore subject to biases in reporting. The purpose of 
this study was to examine data generated from documentation of CODE-5 medical 
emergency events at the University at Buffalo School of Dental Medicine over an 
eight-and-a-half-year period. The incidence of emergencies was found to be 164 
events per million patient visits, which is lower than reported in previous 
studies. Most emergencies involved suspected cardiovascular events, syncope, 
complications related to local anesthesia, and hypoglycemia. Twenty percent of 
emergencies involved people who were in the building for reasons other than to 
receive dental care, underscoring the need for an operational CODE-5 system 
whenever a building is occupied. We suggest strategies to reduce the incidence 
of medical emergencies and increase ability to manage those that do occur.

